result.execSummary:
The defendant Felecia R. Busch was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs [Modifiers: as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

case called at 9:50am. [MK]
Defendant Felecia R. Busch in court with Attorney Yelena Zarwell.  ADA Brookellen Teuber appears for the State of Wisconsin. 
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights given; plea of " No Contest " entered on Count #1; factual basis stipulated; the Court accepts the plea, finds Ms. Busch guilty of Count #1, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #2.

On Count # 1, the Court withholds sentence, and places Ms. Busch on Probation for three years, with conditions:

--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with all recommended treatment
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, and counseling as required by the Agent
--to attend two NA or AA meetings per week for the first six months of the Probation term, and thereafter as directed by the Agent 
--to maintain absolute sobriety:  no possession or consumption of alcohol; no possession or consumption of controlled substances without a valid prescription
--to take all prescribed medications only as prescribed
--no possession of any drug parphernalia including not to possess any syringes unless it is for the administration of a prescribed medication that requires a syringe
--no presence in bars, taverns, liquor stores
--to submit to random testing for illegal drug use; this is to occur at least two time per month for the first year of Probation, and thereafter as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--no direct or indirect contact with Benjamin Zautner
--to obtain/maintain employment and/or education program as approved by the Agent
--to comply with DNA sample provision upon request
--to pay costs of $268 plus $250 DNA surcharge

Service of Complaint admitted; reading waived; charges and maximum penalties recited
Court finds that it states probable cause to support both counts.
Bail/Bond recommendations presented by counsel.

Court requires $2,500.00 signature bond, with conditions: 
-No possession or ingestion of illegal drugs 
-No possession of drug paraphernalia to include needles and syringes
-No contact with Benjamin Zautner
-Not to drive under any circumstance
-Defendant may return to residence that she has property at that is occupied by Benjamin Zautners one time with law enforcement to obtain her personal belongings including any vehicle that may belong to her, Defendant must arrange to go to residence through a third party not directly with Mr. Zautner.
-Defendant must appear at the District Attorneys Office for the Pretrial Conference on 7/16/14 no later than 10:20 am
